    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. i guess the problem is that even with limits, it feels like these new requests just slowly seep in and take over the whole sprint. it's hard to say no when they say it's \"urgent.\" how do i actually handle the \"creep\" part when it's happening in real time? like, what's the formal process for stopping it?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "To handle scope creep in real-time, try using the 'Stop Doing' technique, where you and your team immediately stop working on the non-essential feature and prioritize the existing tasks in the sprint. When the stakeholder says an item is urgent but not that critical, remind them to also consider the impact on the team's overall velocity and consequence of stopping the sprint's momentum.\n\nAnother technique is the 'Comfortable protest trick', if the team decides that the request isn't feasible with the time available for the current sprint, it's finally ok to reject the request or propose to discuss it further. Sometimes just picking up the phone to communicate \"I love your idea but it can't be done this sprint\".",
      "source": "target",
